commit f1d3b2a3720a53dfd209b41305e06a0d1d0efb18
Author: Babak Bandpey <bb@cocode.dk>
Date:   Thu Apr 23 21:48:24 2026 +0200

    feat: M15b-beta — UDP/DNS via SOCKS5 UDP ASSOCIATE + DoH
    
    Completes the tunnel data path so Chrome on Android can actually
    resolve hostnames through the VPN. Codex architecture review picked
    Option A over upstream DNS-hijacking: keep the SOCKS5 seam, add
    UDP ASSOCIATE to core/socks5, answer port-53 queries inside parvazd
    via DoH over the existing fronter transport. xjasonlyu/tun2socks
    already speaks UDP ASSOCIATE, so no client-side changes.
    
    1. core/socks5 — UDP ASSOCIATE (CMD=0x03)
       - New DatagramHandler interface. Nil → REP=0x07 (legacy behaviour
         preserved for the apps-stub E2E path).
       - Per codex's review: server ignores the request's DST.ADDR/DST.PORT
         (xjasonlyu sends 0.0.0.0:0), uses the per-datagram header as
         authoritative, replies with IP ATYP (domain ATYP would be rejected
         by xjasonlyu's symmetric-NAT check), carries the original
         destination back in the UDP reply header for the same reason.
       - FRAG != 0 datagrams dropped per RFC + xjasonlyu behaviour.
       - TCP control-conn close tears down the association (RFC 1928 §6).
    
    2. core/doh — DoH client
       - RFC 8484 POST application/dns-message to dns.google/dns-query.
       - Zeroes the query ID (§4.1 HTTP-cache friendliness) and restores
         the caller's ID on the response so Android's resolver still
         matches requests to answers.
       - Caller-supplied http.Client. parvazd wires it to a relay-backed
         RoundTripper (core/cmd/parvazd/relay_rt.go) so DoH rides the
         Apps Script envelope — see below for why.
    
    Architecture note — DoH transport.
       First-draft approach was "reuse the fronter target directly"
       (216.239.38.120:443 / SNI=www.google.com / Host=dns.google). Live-
       mode wire test revealed dns.google is NOT served on Google's Apps
       front — returns 404 with Host=dns.google there. 8.8.8.8 does serve
       dns.google, but presents a cert that doesn't match SNI=www.google.com,
       so the TLS handshake fails verification under our fronter. Dialing
       with SNI=dns.google would expose "user is doing DNS" to DPI, which
       is exactly what Parvaz exists to hide.
       Resolution: route DoH through the Apps Script relay. Code.gs fetches
       dns.google/dns-query on the server side; the response body (binary
       wire) survives the envelope's base64 round-trip. Cost is one Apps
       Script quota unit per DNS query (~100/session), perfectly within
       the 20k/day free tier. Preserves identical DPI cover to every other
       tunneled request. Proven live via TestDNS_Live_ResolvesExampleComViaRelay:
       2 A records for example.com in 1.95s end-to-end.
    
    3. core/cmd/parvazd/dns.go — in-process DNS shim
       - Satisfies both socks5.DatagramHandler (UDP/53) and the
         dispatcher's DNSTCPHandler (TCP/53 fallback; RFC 1035 §4.2.2).
       - Hard-gates on the synthetic VPN DNS host (10.0.0.2). Apps
         hitting 1.1.1.1 or a corporate resolver are DROPPED, not
         silently rewritten with Google's answer (codex P2 —
         split-horizon / private zones).
       - AAAA queries answered locally with empty NOERROR. VPN is
         IPv4-only; handing out AAAA records would let Chrome
         Happy-Eyeballs onto paths the VPN can't carry (codex P2).
       - DoH failures synthesise SERVFAIL. Previously silent drops
         forced Android's resolver to wait out multi-second retry
         budget (codex P2).
    
    4. core/dispatcher — TCP/53 fallback route
       - New DNSTCPHandler + DNSHost/DNSPort fields. CONNECTs to
         <DNSHost>:<DNSPort> return a pipe wired to ServeTCP instead of
         the usual AllowList/SNI/MITM paths. Without this a TC=1 UDP
         response would trigger TCP/53 that the MITM path can't serve
         (codex P2).
    
    5. core/cmd/parvazd — wiring
       - buildPipeline only wires the DNS shim when cfg.TunFD > 0.
         Pre-M15b-beta the apps-stub E2E flow still gets the old
         REP=0x07 UDP rejection — normal DNS like 8.8.8.8:53 isn't
         silently swallowed by a handler that only answers 10.0.0.2:53
         (codex P3).
       - DNSListenHost config (default 10.0.0.2) configurable via
         stdin JSON for tests.
    
    6. app — Kotlin TUN setup
       - ParvazVpnService.DNS_SERVER changed from 8.8.8.8 to 10.0.0.2.
         Synthetic in-TUN address that parvazd answers for; matches
         the defaultDNSListenHost constant in core/.
    
    Codex review + live-wire verification surfaced:
      Iter 1 — dst-port-only DoH gate (P2), TCP/53 not routed (P2) → fixed.
      Iter 2 — DoH inherits relay -google-ip overrides (P2), legacy SOCKS
        mode wires DNS handler regressively (P3) → fixed.
      Iter 3 — hardcoded fronter ignores cfg (P1), test nil-deref (P3) → fixed.
      Iter 4 — AAAA leaks (P2), silent DoH-failure drops (P2) → fixed.
      Live test — direct-fronter approach returned 404 from dns.google on
        the Apps-front edge; pivoted DoH onto the Apps Script relay
        (architecture note above). Now verified end-to-end against a real
        Code.gs deployment.
    
    Test status:
    - go test -C core -race ./... — all 12 packages green.
    - TestDNS_Live_ResolvesExampleComViaRelay — PASS (live Apps Script).
    - TestRelay_Live_GetExampleCom — PASS (no regression).
    - ./gradlew test assembleDebug — green, 27.7 MB APK.
    - Cross-compile for android/arm64 — clean 17.7 MB libparvaz.so.
    - Emulator walkthrough — still pending; M15b-beta is what unblocks it.
    
    Stacked on feat/android-tun2socks (PR #34); merge order is #34 → this.
    
    Co-Authored-By: Claude Opus 4.7 (1M context) <noreply@anthropic.com>

